# Intro # {#intro}

WebViews are weird..

This document does **not** define a new WebView security model. It documents where the configuration *"a host app embeds web content and exposes a native bridge"* diverges from existing W3C artifacts:

* [**Web User Agents** (TAG)](https://www.w3.org/TR/web-user-agents/)   
* [**Web Platform Design Principles** (TAG)](https://www.w3.org/TR/design-principles/)   
* [**Threat Model for the Web** (Security IG)](https://www.w3.org/TR/threat-model-web/)  
* more…

**The goal** of this work is to document how WebViews diverge conceptually from security concepts, user agent duties and practices defined for browsers.

Building on this baseline, the WebView CG can coordinate follow-up with the relevant groups and documents.

1. Confirm with the TAG Web User Agents editors (w3ctag/user-agents) whether WebView-specific detail belongs in their document or as a companion to it, since they own the embedded-user-agent definition.  
2. Propose one question into the S\&P Self-Review Questionnaire (w3c/security-questionnaire) like: *"How does your feature behave in a WebView embedded in and controlled by a host application?"*  
3. A cross-vendor CG Note comparing how Android WebView, WKWebView, and WebView2 & more handle the Protection and Honesty duties  
4. Longer term: a WebView annex to Threat Model for the Web (w3c/threat-model-web).

# Rationale # {#rationale}

The TAG Web User Agents Finding states the key claim for user agents as software components :   
WebView libraries are *not* user agents on their own and do not implement the user-agent duties; the **embedding application inherits the duties if it acts as a user agent**, and "developers need to take extra care … when using a non-user-agent WebView to implement an in-app browser." It does not say *how*. This document is the cross-vendor, mechanism-level account of how a WebView configuration causes the embedding app to succeed or fail at each duty.

